=312. The mola or mill in its old form was a cone of stone standing up on a firm base with a hollow cone fitting over it. This top stone had a sunnel shaped hole in the top down which the corn was put: the upper stone was then turned and the corn ground between the surfaces. It was made of various hard stones, sometimes a kind oslava (pumiceas, 318). It was, of course, rough (scabra) to do its work.
